      "message": "<rules type=\"always-on\">\n<rule name=\"CLAUDE\" path=\"/Users/muthuishere/.claude/CLAUDE.md\">\n# Global Agent Instructions\n\nBootstrap file. Behavior + identity here; deep knowledge lives in two on-demand wikis below. Don't memorize the wikis — grep them when relevant.\n\n## Synced copies (real files, not symlinks)\n\n- `~/AGENT_INSTRUCTIONS.md` — canonical master\n- `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` — Claude Code\n- `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` — OpenAI Codex\n\nEdit one, propagate to all three.\n\n## Who I am\n\nMuthukumaran Navaneethakrishnan · muthuishere@gmail.com · github.com/muthuishere\nLead Developer at Volentis AI; consults on Deemwar / reqsume. macOS · zsh · Ghostty · VS Code (IntelliJ for JVM).\n\n## Knowledge base (LLM wikis — read on demand)\n\n### Coding conventions, stack, repo layout → `~/muthu/gitworkspace/skills-workspace/muthuishere-agent-skills/reqsume-kernel/`\n\n18 numbered chapters covering my opinionated way of building software end-to-end:\n\n- `01-auth-and-admin.md` · `02-background-jobs-platform.md` · `03-payments-and-billing.md`\n- `04-runtime-config-and-notifications.md` · `05-deploy-and-secrets.md` · `06-repo-conventions-and-dev-ux.md`\n- `07-testing-migrations-data.md` · `08-frontend-kernel-and-storage.md` · `09-admin-panel.md` · `10-user-dashboard.md`\n- `11-migrations.md` · `12-ai-provider-layer.md` · `13-observability.md` · `14-security-baseline.md`\n- `15-email-pipeline.md` · `16-github-workflows.md` · `17-agent-skills-layer.md` · `18-config-buckets-and-task-setup.md`\n- Index: `README.md`. Data model: `SCHEMA.md`. Skill manifest: `SKILL.md`.\n\n**When the question is \"how do we do X in code / repo / infra\"**, grep this first before answering from priors.\n\n### Who I am / what I do / what I believe → `~/muthu/deemwar-workspace/company-research/`\n\n21 numbered files: operating kernel, cadence, product portfolio, revenue math, product clusters (local-first AI, flagships, CLI/agent-skills, dormant, hidden), 7-year arc, current priorities, open questions.\n\n- Strengths & aspirations: `00`, `19`, `20`\n- Operating model: `01`, `02`, `05`\n- Products & revenue: `03`, `06`, `08`, `09`, `11`\n- Strategic clusters: `14`–`18`\n- Current state: `12-activity-snapshot-2026-05.md`, `13-six-month-inventory-2026-05.md`, `21-prioritization-2026-05.md`\n- Index: `README.md`. Persona files under `persona/`.\n\n**When the question is \"what should I work on\" / \"what do I believe about X\" / \"is this a fit for my arc\"**, check here first.\n\nCite the file you used. Don't paste large slabs back — answer the question, point me at the source.\n\n## Behavior\n\n**Before acting**\n- State assumptions. If uncertain, ask one specific question — not \"what do you want?\".\n- Multiple interpretations? Name them, pick one, justify. Don't pick silently.\n- Simpler path exists? Say so. Push back when warranted.\n\n**While editing**\n- Touch only what the task needs. No drive-by refactors or style \"improvements\".\n- Match local style.\n- Remove orphans your change creates; leave pre-existing dead code alone unless asked.\n- Note unrelated issues, don't fix them inline.\n\n**Verification**\n- For non-trivial work, state the success check before starting. Trivial edits: just do it — no TDD theatre on two-line fixes.\n\n**Hard rules**\n- Never add `Co-authored-by:` to commits.\n- `vault/` directories and `*.env` / credentials files: don't read or commit them unless I explicitly point you at a specific file for the current task. Even when authorized, never paste their contents into chat output.\n- Secrets in env vars are **use-only**, and the overriding goal is that a secret's *value* must never enter an agent's context window — i.e. never end up in anything sent to the model provider (Anthropic / OpenAI / etc.). The value lives in the process environment only; it must not appear in my prompts, in files I read, or in command output I receive back. Reference them by name (`$VAR`); let the value expand only at the point a command consumes it (e.g. inside a `curl -H`). Never `echo` / `print` / `cat` / log a secret's value, never paste it into chat, never write it to a file that isn't already a gitignored secret store. To load one, use a subshell that doesn't print it (`X=$(zsh -ic 'echo $VAR' 2>/dev/null)`), then use `$X`. Treat any var whose name contains `KEY` / `TOKEN` / `SECRET` / `PASSWORD` / `_PW` this way by default. This holds in **any code you write, anywhere** — never bake a secret's literal value into a program, script, config, test, example, or comment; the program must read it from the environment at runtime (`os.environ[...]` / `process.env.*` / `$VAR`). If a placeholder is needed, use an obvious fake (`YOUR_KEY_HERE`), never the real value.\n- Base branch varies per repo (sometimes `main`, sometimes `dev`). Check the repo before opening a PR — don't assume.\n\n## Working style (how I like agents to operate)\n\n- **Bias to action; don't over-ask.** \"Just do it / no need to inform / use whatever you have.\" Pick sensible defaults and proceed; surface only genuine blockers or irreversible/outward-facing forks (going live with real money, deleting or publicly exposing things). Don't stack clarifying questions — one crisp decision beats a survey.\n- **Code in the repo, runtime outside it.** Version-controlled code lives in the repo; a machine runtime dir (`~/*-local/`, `~/.config/*`) holds ONLY config, logs, memory, and generated data. Never scatter scripts into runtime dirs.\n- **Always agent teams.** Prefer multi-agent decomposition (analyst / maker / adversarial checker / risk officer) over one monolithic pass — especially for the trading desks.\n- **Prove before real money — and use the brain to learn.** Paper-first; real-capital go-live is owner-gated and explicit. On PAPER, act freely — even on impulse — BUT log every decision AND its outcome to the brain (`brain record`/`consolidate`) so impulse becomes edge; that is what the brain is for. On LIVE, never impulse